"Louis V.R., Russek-Cohen E., Choopun N., Rivera I.N.G., Gangle B., Jiang S.C., Rubin A., Patz J.A., Huq A., Colwell R.R.","Predictability of vibrio cholerae in chesapeake bay",2003,"Applied and Environmental Microbiology","69","5",,"2773","2785",,,10.1128/AEM.69.5.2773-2785.2003,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0037883246&partnerID=40&md5=38868e29d9f7b841d568c2f1d0661482","Center of Marine Biotechnology, Univ. of Maryland Biotech. Institute, 701 E. Pratt St., Baltimore, MD 21202, United States; Department of Animal Sciences, University of Maryland, College Park, MD 20742, United States; Microbiology Department, Biomedical Science Institute, University of São Paulo, CEP 05508-900 Sao Paulo, Sao Paulo, Brazil; Environmental Analysis and Design, University of California, Irvine, CA 92697, United States; Bloomberg School of Public Health, Johns Hopkins University, Baltimore, MD 21205, United States; Department of Cell Biology, University of Maryland, College Park, MD 20742, United States","Louis, V.R., Center of Marine Biotechnology, Univ. of Maryland Biotech. Institute, 701 E. Pratt St., Baltimore, MD 21202, United States; Russek-Cohen, E., Department of Animal Sciences, University of Maryland, College Park, MD 20742, United States; Choopun, N., Center of Marine Biotechnology, Univ. of Maryland Biotech. Institute, 701 E. Pratt St., Baltimore, MD 21202, United States; Rivera, I.N.G., Center of Marine Biotechnology, Univ. of Maryland Biotech. Institute, 701 E. Pratt St., Baltimore, MD 21202, United States, Microbiology Department, Biomedical Science Institute, University of São Paulo, CEP 05508-900 Sao Paulo, Sao Paulo, Brazil; Gangle, B., Center of Marine Biotechnology, Univ. of Maryland Biotech. Institute, 701 E. Pratt St., Baltimore, MD 21202, United States; Jiang, S.C., Environmental Analysis and Design, University of California, Irvine, CA 92697, United States; Rubin, A., Microbiology Department, Biomedical Science Institute, University of São Paulo, CEP 05508-900 Sao Paulo, Sao Paulo, Brazil; Patz, J.A., Bloomberg School of Public Health, Johns Hopkins University, Baltimore, MD 21205, United States; Huq, A., Center of Marine Biotechnology, Univ. of Maryland Biotech. Institute, 701 E. Pratt St., Baltimore, MD 21202, United States; Colwell, R.R., Center of Marine Biotechnology, Univ. of Maryland Biotech. Institute, 701 E. Pratt St., Baltimore, MD 21202, United States, Department of Cell Biology, University of Maryland, College Park, MD 20742, United States","Vibrio cholerae is autochthonous to natural waters and can pose a health risk when it is consumed via untreated water or contaminated shellfish. The correlation between the occurrence of V. cholerae in Chesapeake Bay and environmental factors was investigated over a 3-year period. Water and plankton samples were collected monthly from five shore sampling sites in northern Chesapeake Bay (January 1998 to February 2000) and from research cruise stations on a north-south transect (summers of 1999 and 2000). Enrichment was used to detect culturable V. cholerae, and 21.1% (n = 427) of the samples were positive. As determined by serology tests, the isolates, did not belong to serogroup O1 or O139 associated with cholera epidemics. A direct fluorescent-antibody assay was used to detect V. cholerae O1, and 23.8% (n = 412) of the samples were positive. V. cholerae was more frequently detected during the warmer months and in northern Chesapeake Bay, where the salinity is lower. Statistical models successfully predicted the presence of V. cholerae as a function of water temperature and salinity. Temperatures above 19°C and salinities between 2 and 14 ppt yielded at least a fourfold increase in the number of detectable V. cholerae. The results suggest that salinity variation in Chesapeake Bay or other parameters associated with Susquehanna River inflow contribute to the variability in the occurrence of V. cholerae and that salinity is a useful indicator. Under scenarios of global climate change, increased climate variability, accompanied by higher stream flow rates and warmer temperatures, could favor conditions that increase the occurrence of V. cholerae in Chesapeake Bay.",,"Antibodies; Contamination; Fluorescence; Health risks; Serology; Water treatment; water; bacterium; environmental factor; prediction; species occurrence; article; bacterium culture; bacterium detection; bacterium isolate; bioassay; blood group typing; cholera; climate change; correlation analysis; environmental factor; epidemic; flow rate; fluorescent antibody technique; global climate; nonhuman; parameter; plankton; prediction; river; salinity; sample; seashore; season; serology; statistical model; stream (river); Vibrio cholerae; water flow; water sampling; water temperature; Animals; Base Sequence; DNA, Bacterial; Fresh Water; Humans; Maryland; Seawater; Serotyping; Sodium Chloride; Temperature; Vibrio cholerae; Zooplankton; United States; Bacteria (microorganisms); Negibacteria; Vibrio cholerae",,"water, 7732-18-5; DNA, Bacterial; Sodium Chloride, 7647-14-5",,,,"(1989) Standard Methods for the Examination of Water and Wastewater, 17th Ed., , American Public Health Association, American Water Works Association, and Water Pollution Control Federation, Washington, D.C; Bagchi, K., Echeverria, P., Arthur, J.D., Sethabutr, O., Serichantalergs, O., Hoge, C.W., Epidemic of diarrhea caused by Vibrio cholerae non-O1 that produced heat-stable toxin among Khmers in a camp in Thailand (1993) J. Clin. Microbiol., 31, pp. 1315-1317; Barbieri, E., Fladanzo, L., Fiorentini, C., Pianetti, A., Affone, W., Fabbri, A., Matarrese, P., Donelli, G., Occurrence, diversity, and pathogenicity of halophilic Vibrio spp. and non-O1 Vibrio cholerae from estuarine waters along the Italian Adratic coast (1999) Appl. Environ. Microbiol., 65, pp. 2748-2753; Bik, E.M., Bunschoten, A.E., Gouw, R.D., Mooi, F.R., Genesis of the novel epidemic Vibrio cholerae O139 strain: Evidence for hor